items.content:
@jkbkot @Pontifex One thing the theory computation has taught us is that computation is somewhat hardware independent.
Some may argue that there is something magical about neurons that produce spikes in response to neurotransmitter release by presynaptic neurons.
But that would be like arguing feathered flapping wings are necessary for flight.

@Christophe_501 @Pontifex If we are so perfect, why are we so bad at arithmetics, computing integrals symbolically,  playing chess, go, or poker?
Machines are already more "perfect" than us at these and many other tasks.

(Also, why can we die from diseases if we are so perfect?)

@seanward In my 61 years, I've seen this a few times where a group of disruptors takes a new technology and makes something new out of it. And you're absolutely right to call it out; the story is just beginning.

There's some 14-year-old somewhere who's playing with these tools right now that, in a few years, is going to do something remarkable and capture the world's attention. We don't know who that is yet, but we will learn. All this hatred and noise and stuff is going to fall away. 

I've seen it over and over that when a new disruptive technology comes, everybody resists it and throws eggs at it and bans it and yells and screams about it. But this is just getting going.

